"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806209","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-19","<p>The Government does not comment on UK Special Forces.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-12-19T15:03:08.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806209/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806209/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-13","Armed Forces: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment the Government has been made of the potential effect of proposed changes to the selection processes of the SAS and SBS to increase the number of women recruits on morale, discipline and martial capability within those units.","false","Biography information for Damien Moore","Southport","Damien Moore","119401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806210","Department for Education","false","2017-12-18","<p>As stated in the Social Mobility Action Plan, we will invest £50 million to create more high quality school-based nursery provision for disadvantaged children: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/667690/Social_Mobility_Action_Plan_-_for_printing.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/667690/Social_Mobility_Action_Plan_-_for_printing.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We expect that this investment will contribute to creating and increasing nursery provision in both new and existing schools, including those schools that already provide nursery places and those that do not.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-18T17:08:06.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806210/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806210/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-13","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it is her policy to create a capital fund to support the opening of nurseries in primary schools that do not have the facilities to provide one.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","119402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806211","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-21","<p>The Department for Transport’s recently published strategic vision for rail includes some illustrative examples of potential schemes, but it is not an exhaustive list. The publication makes clear that these schemes require further development and any potential rail line re-opening would need to demonstrate a strong business case where they are seeking Government funding. In the case of the Colne to Skipton railway line, we have yet to see a sufficiently strong business case, and will take into account Transport for the North’s advice on the investment priorities for the North of England.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-21T09:26:45.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806211/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806211/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-13","Skipton-Colne Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Government will take steps to reopen the Colne to Skipton railway line as part  of its proposals in Autumn Budget 2017 further to invest in rail infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","119403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806212","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-21","<p>Following the announcement of the Fund at Autumn Budget, the Government is engaging with the private sector to ensure that it is set up in the most effective way. Further details will be announced in due course.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","119406","2017-12-21T13:17:34.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806212/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806212/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-13","Electric Vehicles: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much of the £400 million electric charging infrastructure fund announced at the Autumn Budget 2017 will be made available for (a) the installation of charge points in London and (b) the installation of 43kW or 50kW rapid charge points in (i) UK and (ii) London.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","119404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806213","Department for Education","false","2017-12-18","<p>11 of the 21 (52 per cent) mainstream primary and all-through schools that have opened since June 2017 have nursery provision. 10 of the 21 (48 per cent) schools opened without nursery provision.</p><p> </p><p>The government has not approved any new school proposals since June 2017. The most recent new school approvals were made in April 2017 when 29 of the 45 (64 per cent) mainstream primary and all-through schools approved included proposals for nursery provision. We will next invite proposals for new schools in early 2018.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","119407","2017-12-18T17:15:22.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806213/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806213/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-13","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what how many and what proportion of primary schools that have opened since June 2017 (a) did and (b) did not have an on-site nursery.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","119405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806214","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-21","<p>Following the announcement of the Fund at Autumn Budget, the Government is engaging with the private sector to ensure that it is set up in the most effective way. Further details will be announced in due course.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","119404","2017-12-21T13:17:34.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806214/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806214/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-13","Electric Vehicles: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress has been made in securing the £200 million private sector investment for charging infrastructure announced in the Autumn Budget 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","119406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806215","Department for Education","false","2017-12-18","<p>11 of the 21 (52 per cent) mainstream primary and all-through schools that have opened since June 2017 have nursery provision. 10 of the 21 (48 per cent) schools opened without nursery provision.</p><p> </p><p>The government has not approved any new school proposals since June 2017. The most recent new school approvals were made in April 2017 when 29 of the 45 (64 per cent) mainstream primary and all-through schools approved included proposals for nursery provision. We will next invite proposals for new schools in early 2018.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","119405","2017-12-18T17:15:22.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806215/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806215/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-13","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of new primary schools that received permission to be built since June 2017 (a) included and (b) did not include plans to build a nursery.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","119407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806216","Department of Health","false","2017-12-18","<p>‘Facing the Facts, Shaping the Future; A draft health and care workforce strategy for England to 2027’ is currently subject to consultation. The consultation will lead to a workforce strategy for the health service, to be published in summer 2018. The precise mental health workforce development budget will be established at this point.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-18T18:15:08.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806216/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806216/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-13","Mental Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the value is of the NHS Improvement Mental Health workforce development budget announced in the Health Education England national workforce strategy.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","119408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806217","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Contracts for Difference (CFD) scheme is applicable to Great Britain. Onshore wind is an established (Pot 1) technology for the purposes of the CFD scheme. No decisions have been taken on running another allocation round for established technologies.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-18T14:12:28.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806217/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806217/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-13","Wind Power: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether Welsh onshore wind projects will be eligible to apply for any future Contracts for Difference Pot 1 auction in the same way as Scottish onshore wind projects in the event that a future auction is held.","false","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","119409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806218","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-22","<p>My department is working with local authorities and with colleagues across Government to support people suffering from loneliness and to develop policies to reduce social isolation.</p><p>Through my department, the Communities Fund is providing resources for 54 partnerships between Local Authorities and communities, some of which are developing projects to help social isolation and loneliness through social prescribing interventions, volunteering and employment. For example, in South Norfolk, a social prescription intervention project will tackle social isolation, reduce use of primary care resources, and help increase access to services in a rural area, and, in Stoke-on-Trent, funding is being used to help communities support older residents, particularly those who are experiencing social isolation and loneliness.</p><p>The planning system also encourages local authorities to consider loneliness and social isolation when making decisions. Paragraph 1.16 of the Housing White Paper confirmed the strengthening of the National Planning Policy Framework so that planning authorities are expected to have clear policies for addressing the housing requirements of groups with particular needs, such as elderly and disabled people and the Neighbourhood Planning Bill introduced a new statutory duty on the Secretary of State to produce guidance for local planning authorities on how their local development documents should meet the housing needs of older and disabled people. Guidance produced will place clearer expectations about planning to meet the needs of older people, including supporting the development of such homes near local services.</p><p>Additionally, our Supported Housing and Disabled Facilities Grant programmes are helping the target populations live as independently as possible within the community, which helps to prevent loneliness.</p><p>All community spaces have an important role to play in preventing loneliness and the Department works closely with local authorities, community groups, and the voluntary and charity sectors to ensure communities know and use the rights they have over their community assets. That can be the local pub, park, community café or local employment services, youth clubs, or social prescribing initiatives. The Pocket Parks Programme, for example, transformed 87 small patches of waste land across England (2015/2016) into community green spaces. Communities not only got a pocket park, but also came together in the planning, execution, and enjoyment of their new community hub, which helped to increase community cohesion and decrease social isolation.</p><p>In 2013-14, the Department of Health also added a loneliness measure to the Adult Social Care Outcomes Framework and Public Health Outcomes Framework and supported the development of a loneliness toolkit for Health and Wellbeing Boards by the Campaign to End Loneliness, which can be found at http://campaigntoendloneliness.org/guidance/. Local authorities can use these measures as guidance to develop interventions to tackle loneliness and social isolation.</p><p />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-22T14:05:46.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806218/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806218/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-13","Loneliness: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps local authorities are taking to ensure elderly and vulnerable people who are without a support network of friends or family during the winter do not suffer from loneliness.","false","Biography information for Damien Moore","Southport","Damien Moore","119410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806219","Department of Health","false","2017-12-18","<p>Due to the complexity and challenge that many children and young people held in the youth justice estate present with, it is often necessary to undertake a more detailed assessment of need, so the most suitable placement can be secured. This can cause delays in the transfer process.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-18T17:12:02.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806219/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806219/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-13","Cookham Wood Young Offender Institution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Annual Report of the Independent Monitoring Board at HM YOI Cookham Wood published in December 2017, what the reasons were for the instances of (a) no available beds and (b) delayed transfers.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","119411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806220","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Department is currently determining two applications for consent under section 36 of the Electricity Act 1989 for onshore wind farms in mid-Wales – the proposed Carnedd Wen and Llanbrynmair wind farms in Powys. Following the quashing of the previous decisions on those applications in December 2015, my Department has carried out further consultation with developers and other interested parties which ended on 4 October 2016. Since then, the responses to that consultation have been carefully assessed and it is anticipated decisions on both applications will be made shortly.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-18T14:11:03.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806220/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806220/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-13","Wind Power: Mid Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress has been made on determining applications under Section 36 of the Electricity Act 2003 for major wind farms in Mid Wales since 4 October 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","119412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806221","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Government proposes to define remote island wind projects as being physically remote and requiring subsea connections from the islands to the Main Interconnected Transmission System. This means that these projects incur unavoidable higher transmission costs, which sets them apart from onshore wind projects located elsewhere in the UK. It is on this basis that the government intends to classify remote island wind as a distinct technology in Pot 2 of the Contracts for Difference scheme. The Government is not proposing to broaden the definition of remote island wind projects in the way that the hon. Member suggests.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-18T16:31:42.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806221/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806221/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-13","Wind Power: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to state aid approval to classify remote island wind as a separate technology in Pot 2 of the CfD scheme, whether he will consider other parts of the UK for inclusion in that classification where remoteness and the lack of electricity grid infrastructure or other reasons mean that it is very difficult to develop onshore wind in those areas.","false","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","119413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806222","Department of Health","false","2017-12-19","<p>We expect mental health providers to work with commissioners and local authorities to ensure there are robust plans in place to support a patient following discharge from hospital as part of the patient’s care plan. Where a patient has been detained under sections 3, 37, 45A, 47 or 48 of the Mental Health Act 1983, the Act requires clinical commissioning groups and local authorities, in co-operation with other agencies, to provide or arrange for the provision of after-care to patients discharged from hospital. The Mental Health Act 1983 Code of Practice sets out these requirements.</p><p> </p><p>Mental health providers are also required to ensure timely follow-up with mental health patients who have been discharged from hospital within seven days.</p><p> </p><p>We are ensuring that every local area has a multi-agency suicide prevention plan in place to ensure all local services including the National Health Service and local authorities, and voluntary and charitable organisations, are working together to implement tailored approaches to reducing suicides in their communities. This includes action to target and reach out to high risk groups such as people who have been in contact with mental health services.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-19T12:15:52.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806222/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/806222/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-13","Suicide: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government is taking to provide support and guidance to patients who have attempted suicide who do not have a network of friends or family after they have been discharged from a mental health unit.","false","Biography information for Damien Moore","Southport","Damien Moore","119414"
